Analysis of service quality in restaurants based on Yelp reviews

Manuel Walser

22nd November 2015

Abstract

This report documents my final Capstone Stone project of the Coursera Data Science specialisation track. It uses the data set of the official Yelp Challange 2015 to analyze the customer happyness about the service in restaurants. The dataset contains about 1.5 million reviews about 200 thousand restaurants in 10 cities in the USA, UK and Germany. All english sentences about service and staff have been rated with a sentiment dictionary (Hu and Liu) regarding there positive or negative polarity. Since no residence was given for the users a simple predictor has been constructed to predict the residence base on review counts and doctor visits. Finally the results have been aggreate the differences between cities and local or foreign visitors has been analysed. No significant differences in service quality could be found between different cities and visitor groups. However there is clear correlation between the rating of a business and the extract service quality.

Introduction

The main goal of this analysis is to extract quantitative information about the service quality from Yelp reviews. This requires the application of text extraction and sentiment analysis methods to obtain a quantitive rating for the service quality of each business. In second step this information is used to analyse the service quality between different cities and visitor groups. One would assume that visitors are quite sensitive to the service quality in the rating of a business. This hypotheses should also be verified for the results. The following question will be analysed and answered in this report.

  • Are there any significant differences between the service quality in different cities?
  • Are there any significant differences between the ratings of local and foreign users?
  • Is the service quality an important factor for the rating of a business?

Furthermore, the results can be interesting for owners of a business who would like to understand how their customers perceive the service quality. A quick analysis of the given dataset shows that 63% of the reviews are written for restaurants.

Methods and Data

Data sources

The original data set can be downloaded from the homepage of the 6th round of the Yelp Dataset Challange. Otherwise no other additional data has been used. The ZIP file includes 5 JONS files containing data about businesses, reviews, users, tips and checkins. The total size of the unpacked files is about 2 GB. For this report only the first three files are necessary. The data of the tips and checkin files is not used. The structure of the original JSON files is documented in detail on the Yelp Dataset Challange homepage.

All calculation have been done with the R version 3.2.2 of R Revolution Enterprise. This distribution of R uses multiple cores for certain mathematical operations. To speed up the calculation further, the parallel package is used occasionally. However the performance of the scripts is still a problem and many steps take hours to evaluate.

Since I think restaurants are the most interesting category to analyse the service quality, the results in this report are restricted to restaurants only. The other two categories with many reviews are Nightlive (13%) and Food (12%). All other categories have 6% or less of reviews. In total this subset contains about 990’000 reviews about 20’000 restaurants in 10 cities from 220’000 users.

Data cleanup

The JSON files have been imported with the jsonlite package into R. The import script normalizes columns with multiple values and converts date and factor variables to the correct datatypes.

Language detection of reviews

At the beginning all reviews have been included in the analysis. Since the results of the sentiment analysis were significantly distorted from non-english reviews, all non-English reviews have been excluded from the analyses. It would require additional effort to included sentiment dictionaries in other languages to obtain useful predictions for these reviews. Over 99% of the reviews are written in english. Further there are several tousand reviews written in german and french. A few reviews are written in other languages like Chinese, Spanish, Dutch and others. Ignoring non-English comments is only a problem in Karlsruhe, because here most reviews are written in German. There for Karsruhe no predictions are included in the report.

To identify the language of each review the ‘textcat’ package has been used. It compares the n-gram profile of a text with an included profile db. This method works well for longer reviews, however short reviews are often misclassified. After restricting the languages to the most common three languages only very few short comments, e.g. ‘terrible service’, where still wrongly classfied.

Service quality from sentiment analysis of reviews

First, all reviews have been splitted into sentences. To split the sentences the sentence splitter from the openNLP package has been used. Next all sentences with the words ‘service’ and ‘staff’ have been filtered. Finally every sentences has been rated with a standard sentiment dictionary (Hu and Liu, 2004) into a positive or negative polarity. To calculate the polarity the qdap package has been used. Finally the sentiment analysis resulted in 510’000 ratings of the service quality of 20’000 restaurants. The ratings have been check manually for about 100 cases to see if the algorithms works as expected.

The obtained polarity have been aggregated by business or regions. Beside the mean polarity of each group I have tried to use compare standardized polarities, too. The standardized polarity is calculated by the ratio of the average polarity divided by the standard deviation for each restaurant. For restaurants with a large number of reviews this is a good indicator, because restaurants with smaller standard deviation are rewarded with a better standardized polarity. However for restaurants with a small number of reviews (n<=20) the average polarity is a more stable indicator for the polarity.

Grouping of cities into region

The dataset contains businesses in 378 cities. These cities have been cluster with a k-means algorithm into 10 regions around eight cities in the USA (Montreal, Phoenix, Charlotte, Las Vega, Pittsburgh, Madison, Waterloo, Urbana), Edinburgh in Great Britain and Karsruhe in Germany.

Residence predictor

Unfortunately the given dataset does not contain any information about the residence of the users. Since I was interested to know if there are significant difference in the rating of users from different regions, the residence of the users had to be predicted. Since no labelled test data was available, no supervised algorithms could be used. The implemented algorithm is based on review counts. It uses the following two assumptions. First, users write visit and write most reviews in the region were they live. Second, users usually visit and rate doctors in their home town. So the implemented algorithm counts the reviews for each user in each region and assigns the region with most reviews as his residence. However the algorithm has only been applied for users who have written at least 5 reviews or 1 doctor review.

Both predictors, the one based all reviews and the one based doctor visits agree for over 99% of the users. This is a good indictor that the predictor works as expected. Of course is not perfect, and some people maybe relocated.

Results

City ranking by median service quality

The first goal of the study was to calculate the average service quality of the 10 different regions. First all service ratings have been aggregated by restaurants. Only restaurant with five or more comments have been included in the next step. Second the ratings for each restaurant are aggregate by region. The following boxplot shows the distribution of the ratings of the restaurant in each region. The numbers in parenthesis indicate the number of rated restaurants in this region. The german city Karlsruhe does not appear in the plot because there where only 35 english comments for this region. Since the distribution of the ratings are slightly skewed, they are ordered according to the median service quality.

From the boxplot we can see that the average quality is best in Edinburgh (median=0.40), and worst in Urbana (0.30). However the differences between the service quality are not significant because the standard deviation is around 0.2 for all regions. If the businesses with less than five comments are included, the main result does not change. However there more extreme ratings and the variance increases. The best and worst regions are still the same, however the order of the regions in the middle changes slightly.

Service quality rating of locals and foreigners

The second goal is to investigate the rating behaviour of locals and foreign customers. The following plot shows the distribution of the ratings of locals and foreign customers.

The histograms of both groups are very similar. The median service quality rating of locals is 0.35 (n=323521), and of foreigners it is 0.37 (n=9537). The difference between the two medians is statistically not significant. So we can conclude that people apply the same criteria in there reviews for local and foreign restaurants.

Correlation between restaurant rating and service quality

The last goal was to analyse the impact of the service quality to the star rating of a restaurant. One would asume that the service quality is a very important factor for the users. This is confirmed by the following plot showing the correlation between the average stars of a restaurant and the rating of the service quality. Each comment about the service quality is represented by a point in the plot. Since the business are rated by one to five stars, the points cumulate around the integer and typical fractional values.

A linear model fits very well to this distribution. The linear model is given by the equation service quality = -0.4 + 0.22 stars. The R-squared value of the correlation is NULL. The correlation is strongly significant.

Discussion

The study shows that it is possible to extract quantitive information about the service quality from textual reviews. So it is possible to rank the businesses by service quality and to provide users of platform as Yelp additional filtering options. The service quality is strongly correlated with the overall rating of a business. This finding is not surprising, however it is very important for business owners who want to trake and improve their rating and customer happyness.

No significant differences could be found between the average service quality of the ten given cities in the USA, UK and Germany. So it is not possible to make any general statements about cultural differences between the regions and countries under investigation. The winner of the city ranking is Edinburgh. It’s a good tip to visit this city at the next opportunity. Since the residence of the users was not given in the dataset, it was more difficult to investigate the rating behaviour of different user groups than expected. A simple predictor based on review counts has been used to predict the residence. A comparision of the reviews of local and foreign customers does not show a significant difference. It’s very good to see that people use the same benchmarks for rating local and foreign businesses.

The analysis provides many options for improvements. The first would be to include other languages such as german to better. This would be mandatory to compare cultural difference between different countries in more detail. Many comments contain a lot of typos and slang words. It would be interesting to know if the rating quality could be improved by applying additional auto-correction algorithms.

I would like make one final comment about the performance of R. To me it does not seem to be the right tool to make this kind of analysis. Many simple transformation as importing the data, split sentences or calculating polarities take hours, if not days, to run. It is possible to speed up the calculations with different tricks subsetting data and parallizing takes, however it takes a lot of time to find out what helps best. It’s possible also possible to sample the data at the beginning, but many problems only appear if one works with the complete data set, e.g. special and extreme values that break the code. Since text extraction algorithms are not very precise, one needs already quite a bit dataset to get resonalable values for the comparision of individual cities and user groups. So in the future I would like to invest some more time in using tools that are better suited for big data analysis.
